    "body": "## Problem\r\n\r\n- Empty ranges have different `<`, `<=`, `has` and `intersect` semantics compared to regular ranges.\r\n- `to_inclusive_pos` assumes that the end position of a range is exclusive, which is not true for empty ranges\r\n\r\n## Solution\r\n\r\nSpecial case empty ranges in all these operations",
    "closed_at": "2026-05-08T09:17:01Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "_links": {
                "html": {
                    "href": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/39474#discussion_r3207655307"
                },
                "pull_request": {
                    "href": "https://api.github.com/repos/neovim/neovim/pulls/39474"
                },
                "self": {
                    "href": "https://api.github.com/repos/neovim/neovim/pulls/comments/3207655307"
                }
            },
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> Asymmetry in __lt/__le: The guards only handle r1:is_empty(), not r2:is_empty(). When r2 is empty at position P and r1 is not, the existing path still runs and r1 < r2 becomes \"r1's inclusive end is before P\"",
            "commit_id": "d09981ff86cdbf6d19a13f7c9e78b0e8c0419a83",
            "created_at": "2026-05-08T09:16:02Z",
            "diff_hunk": "@@ -164,6 +164,10 @@ end\n ---@param r1 vim.Range\n ---@param r2 vim.Range\n function M.__lt(r1, r2)",
